Challenge¶

The business model is subscription based. They have different insurance products and we have a wide variety of features available per user, some of which can change over time.

The task is to create a model that predicts the customer lifetime value (aka LTV) of a customer for the next 12 months. This metric is the sum of the monthly commission we collect from a customer during the first 12 months since they join us, plus the one time commission from additional products they might purchase (cross sell). The customers can cancel their subscription at any time.

  • Problem was three-fold:
    • how to merge the data
    • LTV definition
    • How to train/test the model

    months = ((datetime.now() - x)/np.timedelta64(1, 'Y'))
    return int(months) + 1

def active_months(x, y):
    
    if pd.isnull(y):
        y = datetime.now()
        
    months = ((y - x)/np.timedelta64(1, 'M'))
    return int(months)

LTV Calculation¶

Calculate Monthly Commissions for the First 12 Months: Identify the monthly commissions earned from each customer for the first 12 months after they join. This could include premiums or other regular payment streams.

$$\text{Monthly Commissions} = \sum_{i=1}^{12} \text{Commission}_{\text{month}_i}$$

Calculate One-Time Commissions from Cross-Sell Products: Identify any additional products that were purchased by the customer during that 12-month period, and sum the commissions earned from these products.

Cross-Sell Commissions

$$ \text{Cross-Sell Commissions} = \sum \text{Commission}_{\text{cross-sell products}} $$

Sum the Monthly Commissions and Cross-Sell Commissions:

$$ \text{LTV} = \text{Monthly Commissions} + \text{Cross-Sell Commissions} $$
In [52]:
def compute_revenue(x):
    
    commission = x["commission"].dropna().unique().tolist()[0]
    
    date_cutoff = x["customer_started_at"].iloc[0] + pd.DateOffset(months=12)
    
    total_commission_cross = np.sum(x[x["customer_started_at_cross"] <= date_cutoff]["commission_cross"].dropna())
        
    tenure = x["tenure_months"].dropna().unique().tolist()[0]
    
    product_seq = x["product"].dropna().unique().tolist()
    
    
    
    if tenure > 12:
        revenue = commission * 12 + total_commission_cross
    if tenure <= 12:
        revenue = commission * tenure + total_commission_cross
        
    cross_bool = total_commission_cross > 0
        
    return revenue, cross_bool, product_seq

In [55]:
df['customer_started_at'] = pd.to_datetime(df['customer_started_at'])
df['customer_churned_at'] = pd.to_datetime(df['customer_churned_at'])
df['tenure'] = np.where(df['customer_churned_at'].isnull(), datetime.now() - df['customer_started_at'], df['customer_churned_at'] - df['customer_started_at'])
df['tenure'] = df['tenure'].dt.days


df['tenure_months'] = df['tenure'] // 30
df['tenure_years'] = df['tenure'] // 365


# Add temporal features
df['month'] = df['customer_started_at'].dt.month
df['quarter'] = df['customer_started_at'].dt.quarter

# Preprocess cross-sell data
cross_sell['date'] = pd.to_datetime(cross_sell['date'])

cross_sell = cross_sell.groupby(['user_id', 'product', 'date']).agg({"commission":"sum"}).reset_index()

In [68]:
cat_cols = []
target_cols = []
num_cols = []
for c in dfmodel.columns:
    col_type = dfmodel[c].dtype
    if c != "ltv":
        if col_type == "object" or col_type.name == "category":
            dfmodel[c] = dfmodel[c].astype('category')
            cat_cols.append(c)
        elif col_type == "float64" or col_type == "int64":
            num_cols.append(c)
    else:
        target_cols.append(c)

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

We will pick the best model from our dataframe above and perform a gridsearch with optuna to find the best "settings" (hyperparameters) for the algorithms.

In [84]:
import optuna
from optuna.integration import LightGBMPruningCallback

from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

def objective(trial, X, y):
    param_grid = {
        # "device_type": trial.suggest_categorical("device_type", ['gpu']),
        "n_estimators": trial.suggest_categorical("n_estimators", [10000]),
        "learning_rate": trial.suggest_float("learning_rate", 0.01, 0.3),
        "num_leaves": trial.suggest_int("num_leaves", 20, 3000, step=20),
        "max_depth": trial.suggest_int("max_depth", 3, 12),
        "min_data_in_leaf": trial.suggest_int("min_data_in_leaf", 200, 10000, step=100),
        "lambda_l1": trial.suggest_int("lambda_l1", 0, 100, step=5),
        "lambda_l2": trial.suggest_int("lambda_l2", 0, 100, step=5),
        "min_gain_to_split": trial.suggest_float("min_gain_to_split", 0, 15),
        "bagging_fraction": trial.suggest_float(
            "bagging_fraction", 0.2, 0.95, step=0.1
        ),
        "bagging_freq": trial.suggest_categorical("bagging_freq", [1]),
        "feature_fraction": trial.suggest_float(
            "feature_fraction", 0.2, 0.95, step=0.1
        ),
    }

    fold_idx = np.arange(1, 6)

    cv_scores = []
    for idx in fold_idx:
        
        train_df = dfmodel[dfmodel["12m_p"] <= idx]
        test_df = dfmodel[dfmodel["12m_p"] == idx + 1]
        
        X_train = train_df.drop(columns=["customer_started_at", "customer_churned_at", "ltv", "12m_p"])
        X_test = test_df.drop(columns=["customer_started_at", "customer_churned_at", "ltv", "12m_p"])

        y_train = train_df["ltv"]
        y_test = test_df["ltv"]
    

        model = lgb.LGBMRegressor(objective="l2", verbosity=-1, **param_grid)
        model.fit(
            X_train,
            y_train,
            eval_set=[(X_test, y_test)],
            eval_metric="l2",
            callbacks=[
                LightGBMPruningCallback(trial, "l2")
            ],
        )
        
        preds = model.predict(X_test)

        cv_scores.append(mean_squared_error(y_test, preds))

    return np.mean(np.array(cv_scores))

Able to reduce MSE 50%¶

Business Impact¶

One way to test the model from a business perspective is to look at business KPIs.

KPIs:¶

  • Revenue
  • Churn

Objectives:¶

  • Revenue Increase
  • Churn Reduction

Estimate Impact of Reduced Churn¶

Given we only have the LTV model, here is how I could calculate an estimate of reduced churn:

  • Get number of customers from shape of training data
  • Calculate baseline churn rate from churn column in training data
  • Make predictions with LTV model on training data
  • Select top 20% of customers by predicted LTV (high value segment)
  • Assume we can reduce churn by 50% in this segment through targeting
  • Calculate number of retained customers based on segment size and 50% reduction
  • Subtract retained customers from overall baseline churn to get new churn rate
  • Compare new churn rate to baseline to estimate impact of targeting high value customers
In [87]:
# Get number of customers 
n_customers = X_train.shape[0]

# Get baseline churn rate
baseline_churn = X_train['churn'].mean() 

# Get top 20% of customers by predicted LTV
ltv_pred = clf.predict(X_train)
top_indices = ltv_pred.argsort()[-int(0.2*n_customers):]

# Assume 5% churn reduction in this segment
retained = int(len(top_indices) * 0.05)

# Calculate new overall churn rate
prev_churn = n_customers * baseline_churn
new_churn = (prev_churn - retained) / n_customers
